docs.lead_paragraph: From Mexico to the United Kingdom, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).

headline.main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

docs.abstract: In 1988, Joe Biden was prone to embellishment. Hints of that linger today. But unlike then, his message to voters is clear: He’s a stabilizing statesman in a tumultuous time.
docs.snippet: In 1988, Joe Biden was prone to embellishment. Hints of that linger today. But unlike then, his message to voters is clear: He’s a stabilizing statesman in a tumultuous time.
docs.lead_paragraph: Joe Biden was riffing again — an R.F.K. anecdote, a word about “civil wrongs,” a meandering joke about the baseball commissioner — and aides knew enough to worry a little.

headline.main: Biden’s First Run for President Was a Calamity. Some Missteps Still Resonate.
headline.print_headline: ‘Dumb Things’: Disastrous ’88 Campaign Still Echoes for Biden

docs.abstract: In the absence of hardball questions, Mr. Buttigieg delved into policy, at points appearing to work through the details of his ideas in real time.

docs.lead_paragraph: Pete Buttigieg thrives in town halls: It was one of them, on CNN in March, that initially sent him near the top of what is now a 23-person Democratic presidential field. But this one was different.

headline.main: Pete Buttigieg Finds a Friendly Crowd at MSNBC Town Hall

docs.abstract: The Vermont senator, weighing another presidential bid, is trying to calm unease about reports of sexism and discrimination in his 2016 campaign.

docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Bernie Sanders, accelerating his efforts to contain the damage from reports of sexism and harassment during his 2016 presidential campaign, plans to meet on Wednesday with a group of former staff members seeking assurances of better practices if he runs again in 2020.

headline.main: Bernie Sanders, Addressing Sexism Complaints, Will Meet With Former Staff Members

docs.abstract: The candidates argued that the president is a bigot and outlined their plans to uplift black people at the civil rights group’s convention in Detroit.
docs.snippet: The candidates argued that the president is a bigot and outlined their plans to uplift black people at the civil rights group’s convention in Detroit.
docs.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — As “Robert Mueller Wednesday” overtook Washington, with the nation transfixed on the congressional testimony of the special counsel who investigated Russian interference in the 2016 election, Democratic presidential hopefuls laid out a different case: that President Trump is a bigot who unduly harms black communities.

headline.main: At N.A.A.C.P. Forum, 2020 Democrats Say Trump Harms Black Communities
headline.print_headline: At N.A.A.C.P. Convention, Candidates Keep Outrage Focused on the President

docs.abstract: Mr. Bell defeated Robert P. McCulloch, the county official who oversaw the investigation into the police shooting of Michael Brown in 2014.
docs.snippet: Mr. Bell defeated Robert P. McCulloch, the county official who oversaw the investigation into the police shooting of Michael Brown in 2014.
docs.lead_paragraph: Wesley Bell, a reform-minded City Council member from Ferguson, Mo., declared victory in the Democratic primary for St. Louis County prosecutor Tuesday evening, saying he had ousted the longtime incumbent Robert P. McCulloch, who came under national scrutiny for his handling of the investigation into the 2014 shooting of a black teenager by a white police officer.

headline.main: Wesley Bell, Ferguson Councilman, Unseats St. Louis County Prosecutor
